<s1 id=ToConvertCalendarTA>To Upgrade Your Calendar Data
        <idx><computer>sdtcm_convert<\computer><sort>sdtcm_convert<\idx>
        <idx>converting calendar data formats<\idx>
        <idx>data formats, converting<\idx>
        <idx>formats, converting calendar data<\idx>

<p>Use <computer>sdtcm_convert<\computer> to convert your calendar 
(callog) file from OpenWindows format (version 3) to the new standard
format used in CDE (version 4) or vice versa.

<newline>&empty;

<note>
<computer>sdtcm_convert<\computer> must be run by the super-user (root) or the 
owner of the calendar.
<\note>

<newline>&empty;

<p>To determine the data format of your calendar:

<list bullet>
<item>Choose About Calendar from Calendar's Help menu.
<p>The About Calendar dialog box displays your calendar's data version.
<\list>

<newline>&empty;

<p>To convert the calendar <emph>calendar-name<\emph> from 
version 3 to version 4 data format:

<ex>
example% <term nogloss>sdtcm_convert -v 4 <\term><emph>calendar-name<\emph>
Loading the calendar ...
Doing conversion ...
Writing out new file ...
Conversion done successfully.
Total number of appointments                  = 709
Number of one-time appointments converted     = 670
Number of repeating appointments converted    = 39
Number of one-time appointments pruned        = 0
Number of repeating appointments pruned       = 0
The original file is saved in /var/spool/calendar/calorig.<emph>calendar-name<\emph>
example%
<\ex>

<p>The version 3 data format includes the appointment date, start and end 
times, repeat interval, information about the appointment, and reminders.  
The version 4 data format includes additional privacy and access appointment 
attributes.

<newline>&empty;

<note>The OpenWindows calendar server (which supports version 3 or 
earlier data format) does not support the version 4 data format used
in CDE.  If you need to switch back to the OpenWindows calendar 
server and you have a calendar that supports version 4 data, you should 
convert your calendar to the version 3 data format before switching the 
server.  However, all calendar attributes
not supported by the OpenWindows calendar server will be lost.
<\note>

<newline>&empty;

<p>To convert the calendar <emph>calendar-name<\emph> from version 4 to
version 3 data format:

<ex>
example% <term nogloss>sdtcm_convert -v 3 <\term><emph>calendar-name<\emph>
Loading the calendar ...

WARNING!! Data will be lost when converting version 4 data format
back to version 3 data format.

Do you want to continue? (Y/N) Y

Doing conversion ...
Writing out new file ...
Conversion done successfully.
Total number of appointments                  = 209
Number of one-time appointments converted     = 190
Number of repeating appointments converted    = 19
Number of one-time appointments pruned        = 0
Number of repeating appointments pruned       = 0
The original file is saved in /var/spool/calendar/calorig.<emph>calendar-name<\emph>
example%
<\ex>

<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref CalendarConvertUtility>
<item> <xref ToPruneCalendarTA>
<item> <xref CalendarCommandSyntax>
<\list>


<s1 id=ToPruneCalendarTA>To Remove Old Appointments from Your Calendar
	<idx>pruning old appointments from your calendar<\idx> 
	<idx>removing old appointments from your calendar<\idx>
	<idx>old appointments, removing from your calendar<\idx>

<p>You may wish to remove (prune) old appointments from your calendar 
to improve performance or decrease clutter.

<p>To prune the calendar <emph>calendar-name<\emph> of appointments before July 1st, 1997
and put the backup of the original calendar file in the directory 
<computer>/export/backup<\computer>:

<ex>
example% <term nogloss>sdtcm_convert -s 7/1/97 -d /export/backup <\term><emph>calendar-name<\emph>
Loading the calendar ...
Doing conversion ...
Writing out new file ...
Conversion done successfully.
Total number of appointments                  = 252
Number of one-time appointments converted     = 190
Number of repeating appointments converted    = 19
Number of one-time appointments pruned        = 43
Number of repeating appointments pruned       = 0
The original file is saved in /var/spool/calendar/calorig.<emph>calendar-name<\emph> 
example% 
<\ex>

<newline>&empty;

<note>The date format for <computer>sdtcm_convert<\computer> 
is mm/dd/yy in all locales.
<\note>

<newline>&empty;

<p>To convert the calendar <emph>calendar-name<\emph> to version 4 data format
starting from 1/1/97:

<ex>
example% <term nogloss>sdtcm_convert -v 4 -s 1/1/97 <\term><emph>calendar-name<\emph>
Loadint the calendar ...
Doing conversion ...
Writing out new file ... 
Conversion done successfully. 
Total number of appointments                  = 709 
Number of one-time appointments converted     = 233
Number of repeating appointments converted    = 19 
Number of one-time appointments pruned        = 437 
Number of repeating appointments pruned       = 20 
The original file is saved in /var/spool/calendar/calorig.<emph>calendar-name<\emph>  
example% 
<\ex>

<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref CalendarConvertUtility>
<item> <xref ToConvertCalendarTA>
<item> <xref CalendarCommandSyntax>
<\list>


